# Boilerplate Development Rules

- Use the NestJS framework.
- Every API must have Swagger documentation.
- Every API must have versioning in the path.
- Mandatory minimum 85% unit test coverage using Jest.
- Mandatory minimum 80% E2E test coverage using Playwright (when applicable).
- Mandatory minimum 80% integrated test coverage.
- Use ESLint.
- Do not contemplate only success scenarios; think about error scenarios, failures, and contingencies for a robust application.
- Always log all warnings and errors in the `storage/log` folder.
- Never use mocks; implementation must always be functional.
- Swagger documentation must always be at `/doc`.
- ALWAYS provide internationalization (multi-language), initially with Brazilian Portuguese as the default.
- Each delivery/task must be tested and meet minimum coverage for all applicable test types.
- All files generated by the application or uploaded by users must be organized in folders within the `storage` folder.
- All programming and comments must always be in English.
- All programming must follow SOLID best practices and System Design principles.
- All programming must have comments explaining each section, function, file, module, provider, etc. (No need to comment every line, but comment complex logic).
- Provide a `readme.md` in the project root with installation, build, and start instructions in English.
- Configure `package.json` with the `start` command.
- Configure `package.json` with the `stop` command.
- Configure `package.json` with `test:$` commands for unit, integrated, and E2E tests.
- Create and always update the `.gitignore` file as needed.
- Use AWS Secrets Manager for credentials.
- ALWAYS use migrations whenever the application has a database or external database connection.
- NEVER delete anything from the database; always mark as `deleted: true`.
- ALWAYS inherit from `BaseProvider` when creating new infrastructure providers (AWS, AI, etc.) to ensure standardized logs and error handling.
- EXTREME TYPE STRICTNESS: The use of `any` or loose type casting (`as any`) is strictly forbidden. Always use concrete interfaces or `unknown` with narrowing.
- FOLDER PATTERN CONVENTION: Business logic MUST be organized within `src/modules` and generic infrastructure providers within `src/providers` to minimize technical debt.
- MODULE ISOLATION: Modules MUST be black boxes. Direct imports between business modules are forbidden; use public interfaces or event-driven patterns.
- INTERFACE-FIRST INJECTION: All Providers and Services MUST implement a corresponding Interface. Dependency injection MUST reference the Interface, not the concrete class.
- MANDATORY JSDOC: All public methods, providers, and modules MUST have English JSDoc comments explaining their purpose and complex logic.
- SRP ENFORCEMENT: Classes MUST NOT exceed 200 lines. Methods MUST NOT exceed 15 cognitive complexity points (SonarJS).
- MANDATORY HEALTH ENDPOINTS: Every service MUST implement `/health` and `/ready` endpoints to provide native observability for container orchestrators and monitoring systems.
- ZERO WARNING POLICY: Code MUST be 100% free of warnings and errors in console, logs, and linting. Warnings are treated as blocking errors.
- HARDCODED SECRET DETECTION: The linter MUST be configured to detect and block high-entropy strings and known AWS/API key patterns to prevent credential leakage.
- NO INSECURE TRANSITIVE: The use of `npm overrides` is MANDATORY whenever a transitive dependency fails an `npm audit` in CI. Each override MUST have a corresponding English comment in `package.json` referencing the CVE or justification.
- ALWAYS at the end of each execution, write what can be improved in existing or missing rules, skills, and/or workflows based on the last prompt execution.
